---
import MarketingLayout from "../layouts/MarketingLayout.astro";
---

<MarketingLayout
  title="MailAtlas: Email Access for AI Agents"
  description="MailAtlas turns complex email into clean, agent-readable data. It gives agents a copy of the inbox and outbox they can query, while handling HTML, attachments, embedded images, metadata, exports, and provenance."
>
  <header class="topbar">
    <a class="brand" href="/" aria-label="MailAtlas home">
      <span class="brand-mark" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      <span>MailAtlas</span>
    </a>
    <nav class="topnav" aria-label="Primary">
      <a href="#why">Why</a>
      <a href="#sources">Sources</a>
      <a href="#stores">Stored data</a>
      <a href="/docs/">Docs</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas">GitHub</a>
    </nav>
  </header>

  <main class="landing-main">
    <section class="hero" id="overview">
      <div class="hero-inner">
        <p class="eyebrow">Email tools for AI agents</p>
        <h1>MailAtlas makes email accessible to AI agents.</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          It turns complex email into clean, agent-readable data. Connect your mailbox, import
          archives, export HTML, PDF, or Markdown, and let MailAtlas keep track of embedded images,
          attachments, metadata, and provenance.
        </p>
        <p class="hero-command"><code>python -m pip install mailatlas</code></p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block" id="why">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Why MailAtlas</p>
        <h2>Current email interfaces serve humans, not agents.</h2>
        <p>
          Email looks great in an inbox because it was designed for people. Give the same message to
          an agent as raw source or provider API output and it has to deal with MIME structure,
          rendered HTML, attachments, thread context, and provider-specific metadata.
        </p>
        <p>
          Agents need structured, clean email access that does not pollute their context window.
          MailAtlas gives them an interface for reading email in the cleanest possible way, while
          preserving body content, HTML, attachments, embedded images, metadata, provenance, and the
          overall structure of each message.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fit-stack">
        <article>
          <h3>Use MailAtlas when you need to</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Turn complex email into clean text, HTML, Markdown, PDF, and structured metadata.</li>
            <li>Track embedded images, attachments, source messages, and provenance together.</li>
            <li>Import email from mailboxes, <code>.eml</code> files, or <code>mbox</code> archives.</li>
            <li>Create a copy of the inbox and outbox your agent can query and send from.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block section-muted" id="story">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">How it works</p>
        <h2>Clean email data in a workspace your agent can query.</h2>
      </div>

      <ol class="step-list">
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">01</span>
          <div>
            <h3>An email workspace for every agent</h3>
            <p>
              Use the same workspace from the CLI, Python code, or MCP tools, depending on how your
              agent works.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">02</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Bring email in</h3>
            <p>
              Import from <code>.eml</code> files, <code>mbox</code> archives, Gmail, or selected
              IMAP folders. Use whichever source matches where your email already lives.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">03</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Clean and export the email</h3>
            <p>
              MailAtlas gives agents clean body text, HTML, Markdown, PDF, JSON, attachments,
              embedded images, metadata, and links back to the original message.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="step-index">04</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Send through your provider</h3>
            <p>
              When your agent needs to reply or follow up, MailAtlas sends through SMTP, Cloudflare
              Email Service, or Gmail API OAuth.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block" id="sources">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Sources and outputs</p>
        <h2>Bring email in. Give agents clean data back.</h2>
        <p>
          Connect a live mailbox and keep the agent's email workspace current with watch mode. You
          can also import archived email, export clean documents, and send through your existing
          provider from the same workspace.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="source-list">
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">
          <strong>Live mailboxes</strong>
          <span>
            Use Gmail or IMAP receive when messages still live in a mailbox. Run watch mode when
            your agent needs the workspace to stay current.
          </span>
          <code>sync</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">
          <strong>Email files</strong>
          <span>
            Use file ingest when you already have individual <code>.eml</code> files, directories
            of exported messages, or test fixtures.
          </span>
          <code>.eml</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/examples/mbox-ingest/">
          <strong>Mailbox archives</strong>
          <span>
            Use <code>mbox</code> ingest when you have a mailbox export on disk and want each
            message stored as a document.
          </span>
          <code>mbox</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">
          <strong>Outbound email</strong>
          <span>
            Send email through a configured provider when your agent needs to reply, notify, or
            follow up.
          </span>
          <code>send</code>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block" id="stores">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Email workspace</p>
        <h2>Everything your agent needs to read and work with email.</h2>
        <p>
          MailAtlas stores clean email outputs as ordinary files and uses SQLite for lookup, dedupe,
          exports, provenance, mailbox sync state, and message records.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="source-list storage-list">
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Inbound</strong>
          <span>Original raw email bytes, cleaned body text, normalized HTML snapshots, and metadata.</span>
          <code>raw/ html/ store.db</code>
        </div>
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Assets</strong>
          <span>Extracted inline images and regular file attachments associated with a document.</span>
          <code>assets</code>
        </div>
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Exports</strong>
          <span>JSON, Markdown, HTML, and PDF artifacts written from stored documents.</span>
          <code>exports/</code>
        </div>
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Mailbox sync</strong>
          <span>IMAP sync cursors for manual selected-folder sync.</span>
          <code>store.db</code>
        </div>
        <div class="source-row">
          <strong>Outbound</strong>
          <span>
            Outbound <code>.eml</code> snapshots, body files, copied attachments, recipient metadata,
            provider status, error details, and retry metadata.
          </span>
          <code>outbound/ store.db</code>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="section-note">
        MailAtlas receives from Gmail API or IMAP, including IMAP password or OAuth-token auth. For
        outbound email, it sends through SMTP, Cloudflare Email Service, or Gmail API OAuth.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block section-muted" id="next">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Next steps</p>
        <h2>Pick the first email workflow your agent needs.</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="source-list">
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/installation/">
          <strong>Install MailAtlas</strong>
          <span>Set up the CLI and verify the install with <code>mailatlas doctor</code>.</span>
          <code>install</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">
          <strong>Import a sample email</strong>
          <span>Import a local <code>.eml</code> file and inspect what MailAtlas stores.</span>
          <code>files</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">
          <strong>Connect a mailbox</strong>
          <span>Bring Gmail or selected IMAP folders into the same agent-readable inbox copy.</span>
          <code>imap</code>
        </a>
        <a class="source-row" href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">
          <strong>Set up outbound email</strong>
          <span>Send messages through your existing provider.</span>
          <code>send</code>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="footer-cta">
      <div class="footer-brand">
        <a class="brand" href="/" aria-label="MailAtlas home">
          <span class="brand-mark" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span>MailAtlas</span>
        </a>
        <p>MailAtlas makes email accessible to AI agents by turning complex messages into clean, source-linked data.</p>
      </div>

      <nav class="footer-links" aria-label="Footer">
        <div>
          <h2>Docs</h2>
          <a href="/docs/getting-started/quickstart/">Quickstart</a>
          <a href="/docs/getting-started/manual-imap-sync/">Manual IMAP Sync</a>
          <a href="/docs/providers/outbound-email/">Outbound Email</a>
          <a href="/docs/concepts/workspace-model/">Workspace Model</a>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h2>Project</h2>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas">GitHub</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/examples">Examples</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/sample-data">Sample Data</a>
          <a href="/docs/product/roadmap/">Roadmap</a>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h2>Trust</h2>
          <a href="/docs/product/security-and-privacy/">Security and Privacy</a>
          <a href="mailto:hello@mailatlas.dev">hello@mailatlas.dev</a>
          <a href="https://github.com/mailatlas/mailatlas/issues">Issues</a>
        </div>
      </nav>

      <div class="footer-bottom">
        <span>© 2026 MailAtlas. MIT licensed.</span>
        <span>local-first</span>
      </div>
    </footer>
  </main>
</MarketingLayout>
